---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import WaitlistForm from '../components/WaitlistForm.astro';

const siteUrl = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_SITE_URL || 'https://meridian-a7k2.vercel.app';

const structuredData = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Meridian",
    "url": siteUrl,
    "logo": `${siteUrl}/favicon.svg`,
    "description": "Small-batch specialty coffee roaster sourcing rare single-origin beans from peak-altitude farms."
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "The Story Behind Meridian Coffee",
    "url": `${siteUrl}/about`,
    "description": "How Meridian was built on a single belief: the best coffee grows at the peak."
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": siteUrl },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Our Story", "item": `${siteUrl}/about` }
    ]
  }
];
---
<Base
  title="Our Story | Meridian Specialty Coffee"
  description="Learn how Meridian was built on a single belief: the best coffee grows at the peak. Discover our sourcing philosophy and the farmers we partner with."
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <div class="relative">
    <Nav active="about" />

    <section class="relative px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 pt-16 md:pt-24 pb-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <p class="eyebrow opacity-60 reveal">Our Story</p>
        <h1 class="serif mt-6 text-[clamp(2.5rem,6.5vw,6rem)] leading-[0.95] tracking-[-0.02em] reveal">
          The Story Behind<br/>
          <span class="italic font-light text-copper">Meridian</span> Coffee.
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed opacity-85 reveal">
          Meridian is a small batch coffee roaster built around a single conviction — that the
          finest cups in the world are grown at the peak, hand-picked by people who care, and
          roasted by people who listen. This is how we got here.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="relative px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 pb-20 reveal">
      <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-6xl overflow-hidden rounded-sm">
        <img
          src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1442550528053-c431ecb55509?auto=format&fit=crop&w=1800&q=80"
          alt="Coffee cherries ripening on a high-altitude farm, mountain mist in the background"
          class="h-[340px] md:h-[520px] w-full object-cover"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <div class="grain"></div>
      </div>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-4 max-w-6xl text-xs opacity-60 eyebrow">Huila, Colombia · 1,950m above sea level</p>
    </section>

    <section class="relative px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 pb-24">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl space-y-24">

        <article class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 items-start reveal">
          <div class="md:col-span-3">
            <p class="eyebrow opacity-50">Chapter I</p>
            <p class="serif text-5xl opacity-20 mt-2">01</p>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-9 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed opacity-90">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl leading-tight tracking-tight opacity-100">
              A Belief in Altitude
            </h2>
            <p>
              There is a reason the most celebrated coffees in the world come from mountains. Altitude
              slows a cherry's journey — thinner air, colder nights, longer ripening. A bean that would
              mature in four months at sea level will take nine in the highlands. In those extra months
              the fruit concentrates, sugars settle, and the cup that follows carries complexity that
              cannot be manufactured.
            </p>
            <p>
              Meridian was founded on this: we will only buy coffee grown at or above 1,800 metres.
              It is a narrow rule by design. It excludes most of what is sold as "premium." It forces
              us to travel further, pay more, buy less, and wait for harvests that only come once a
              year. We think that's the point.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 items-start reveal">
          <div class="md:col-span-3">
            <p class="eyebrow opacity-50">Chapter II</p>
            <p class="serif text-5xl opacity-20 mt-2">02</p>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-9 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed opacity-90">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl leading-tight tracking-tight opacity-100">
              The Farmers We Partner With
            </h2>
            <p>
              Every lot Meridian sells can be traced to a single farm, often a single lot within that
              farm. We spend weeks a year at origin — walking drying patios in Yirgacheffe, tasting
              ferment tanks in Huila, watching fog roll off volcanic ridges in Panama. Our partnerships
              are long and unfashionably patient. We commit to multi-year purchase agreements at prices
              that protect the grower from commodity swings, because the grower is the entire story.
            </p>
            <p>
              A farmer who owns their land and can plan three years out will grade their cherries
              differently than one selling to the next buyer that shows up. The cup tells you which
              one harvested it. We taste the difference. We think you will too.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 items-start reveal">
          <div class="md:col-span-3">
            <p class="eyebrow opacity-50">Chapter III</p>
            <p class="serif text-5xl opacity-20 mt-2">03</p>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-9 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed opacity-90">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl leading-tight tracking-tight opacity-100">
              Roasting With Restraint
            </h2>
            <p>
              A good roast is a conversation, not a recipe. Our roastmaster, Ines, learned her craft in
              Copenhagen and refined it through ten years of small batches in Melbourne. Her signature
              is what she doesn't do — she roasts light enough to reveal the farm, not the flame.
              No dark crust, no heavy caramel, no masking. You taste Ethiopia, not our kitchen.
            </p>
            <p>
              Every green bean gets twenty to thirty test-roasts before we approve a profile. Every
              production batch is cupped against the sample the morning we ship. If a roast misses by
              a point, it doesn't leave the roastery. It becomes espresso for the staff.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 items-start reveal">
          <div class="md:col-span-3">
            <p class="eyebrow opacity-50">Chapter IV</p>
            <p class="serif text-5xl opacity-20 mt-2">04</p>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-9 space-y-5 text-lg leading-relaxed opacity-90">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl md:text-4xl leading-tight tracking-tight opacity-100">
              Shipped While It Still Remembers the Farm
            </h2>
            <p>
              Coffee peaks seven to fourteen days after roast. By the time most supermarket bags
              reach a kitchen they have lost their memory of the farm entirely — a tired, flat echo
              of what they once were. Meridian roasts to order. Every bag leaves the roastery within
              forty-eight hours of the roast date printed on the label, so the first cup you pour
              tastes the way the roastmaster intended it to.
            </p>
            <p>
              That is the entire brand, really. Source from the peak. Roast with restraint. Ship
              while it still remembers. If we can do those three things well, we don't need to say
              much else.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="relative px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 py-28 bg-espresso text-cream dark:bg-cream dark:text-ink">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center reveal">
        <p class="eyebrow opacity-70">Be First</p>
        <h2 class="serif mt-4 text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">Join the waitlist for our first roast.</h2>
        <p class="mt-5 opacity-80 max-w-xl mx-auto">
          We're a few weeks out from our first harvest release. Put yourself on the list and we'll
          open the cellar door to you before anyone else.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-10 flex justify-center">
          <WaitlistForm variant="dark" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="relative px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 py-10 border-t border-current/10">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-between gap-4 text-xs opacity-60">
        <p>© {new Date().getFullYear()} Meridian Coffee Roasters.</p>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-6">
          <a href="/" class="hover:opacity-100">Home</a>
          <a href="/#waitlist" class="hover:opacity-100">Waitlist</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </div>
</Base>
